{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647670"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:46:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:46:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18257"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18257"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.65,0.05,0,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10971"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81725"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10971"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18257"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67025"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7228"},{"type":"tags","id":"7233"},{"type":"tags","id":"7234"},{"type":"tags","id":"7418"},{"type":"tags","id":"7430"},{"type":"tags","id":"7432"},{"type":"tags","id":"10244"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25492"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25495"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81725"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct regarding the pectineus muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It is part of the posterior compartment of the thigh","It is innervated by the femoral nerve L2, L3 (and sometimes, the obturator nerve)","It is primarily responsible for knee extension","It is located in the lateral compartment of the thigh","It is innervated solely by the obturator nerve"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epectineus muscle\u003C/strong\u003E receives its primary innervation from the femoral nerve (L2, L3). In some cases, it also receives additional innervation from the obturator nerve, making it a unique transitional muscle between the anterior and medial thigh compartments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELet\u0027s examine why the other statements are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior compartment\u003C/strong\u003E statement is incorrect because the pectineus is actually located in the anterior compartment of the thigh\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eknee extension\u003C/strong\u003E function is incorrect - this is actually performed by the quadriceps muscle group, not the pectineus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral compartment\u003C/strong\u003E location is incorrect - the pectineus is found in the anterior compartment, while the lateral compartment contains different muscles like the tensor fasciae latae\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eobturator nerve\u003C/strong\u003E statement is incorrect because while this nerve may contribute to pectineus innervation, it is not the sole nerve supply\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The pectineus muscle is primarily innervated by the femoral nerve, but it may also receive innervation from the obturator nerve.","The pectineus muscle is located in the anterior compartment of the thigh, not the posterior compartment."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67025"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18257"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67025"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T20:28:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T20:38:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10971"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81725"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","s